WEBVTT

00:06.040 --> 00:06.540
♪

00:13.565 --> 00:16.533
Oh, yeah, this place
was a-booming.

00:16.568 --> 00:19.847
You couldn't get through
this town down there,

00:19.881 --> 00:22.056
but it's dead now.

00:22.091 --> 00:25.094
We had eight or ten coal mines
shut down at one time.

00:25.128 --> 00:29.063
Come on, everybody in here!
Have a seat! Let's go!

00:29.098 --> 00:32.273
It's the same halftime speech
every single week.

00:32.308 --> 00:35.587
♪

00:35.621 --> 00:38.452
There's so much negativity
surrounding this place

00:38.486 --> 00:40.626
that no one ever focuses
on the positive.

00:40.661 --> 00:43.215
They see us as ignorant
or hillbillies.

00:43.250 --> 00:47.185
Overdose capital
of the East Coast.

00:47.219 --> 00:49.428
There's really more here
than just poverty

00:49.463 --> 00:50.878
and illiteracy and drugs.

00:50.912 --> 00:53.260
There's a lot
of good people here.

00:53.294 --> 00:55.745
When you walk on this field,
you better have tunnel vision.

00:55.779 --> 00:57.264
Don't look left.
Don't look right.

00:57.298 --> 00:59.093
You look at that scoreboard,

00:59.128 --> 01:01.268
and that shit burn in your
heart, you understand me?

01:01.302 --> 01:02.959
We got some ground to make up,

01:02.993 --> 01:05.617
but once we make that
ground up, we'll take off.

01:05.651 --> 01:06.756
Let's go!

01:09.448 --> 01:11.312
♪ I took a walk
through this ♪

01:11.347 --> 01:14.488
♪ Beautiful world

01:14.522 --> 01:19.596
♪ Felt the cool rain
on my shoulder ♪

01:19.631 --> 01:23.083
♪ Found something good
in this ♪

01:23.117 --> 01:25.844
♪ Beautiful world

01:25.878 --> 01:31.677
♪ I felt the rain
getting colder ♪

01:31.712 --> 01:35.025
- ♪ La, la
- ♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:35.060 --> 01:36.924
♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:36.958 --> 01:40.859
- ♪ Sha la, la, la
- Sha la, la, la, la ♪

01:40.893 --> 01:46.002
♪ Sha la, la, la, la, la

01:50.282 --> 01:53.699
♪

01:53.734 --> 01:56.461
New York City, where I live.

01:56.495 --> 01:58.359
And it's easy to think,

01:58.394 --> 01:59.981
having lived here
nearly all my life,

02:00.016 --> 02:03.192
that this what America
looks like, thinks like,

02:03.226 --> 02:05.366
that the things that
are important to me

02:05.401 --> 02:06.885
are important to everybody.

02:06.919 --> 02:09.888
That anyplace else
is "out there."

02:09.922 --> 02:11.269
Unthinkable.

02:11.303 --> 02:13.823
Maybe even unknowable.

02:13.857 --> 02:14.357
♪

02:16.000 --> 02:22.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:28.838 --> 02:31.668
600 miles away from
Midtown Manhattan

02:31.703 --> 02:34.326
is McDowell County,
West Virginia.

02:34.361 --> 02:35.983
Another America.

02:36.017 --> 02:38.537
In the mind of many
of my fellow New Yorkers,

02:38.572 --> 02:41.678
the heart of God,
guns and Trump country.

02:41.713 --> 02:44.336
The existential enemy.

02:47.374 --> 02:49.238
♪

02:49.272 --> 02:55.105
♪ There is a place
on God's creation ♪

02:55.140 --> 03:00.110
♪ A place of beauty
beyond compare ♪

03:00.145 --> 03:06.116
♪ Some people say
it's almost heaven ♪

03:06.151 --> 03:10.880
♪ Look for me
and you'll find me there ♪

03:10.914 --> 03:12.847
My daddy always told me,
you know,

03:12.882 --> 03:15.954
those tornados and hurricanes,
they can't get to us.

03:15.988 --> 03:18.405
We're way down in these
mountains, down in the holler,

03:18.439 --> 03:20.269
and these mountains protect us.

03:20.303 --> 03:23.789
Here, if you gonna see the sky,
you got to look up.

03:23.824 --> 03:27.759
♪ You can find me
on the highest mountain ♪

03:29.243 --> 03:34.041
♪ You can find me
in the black coal mines ♪

03:34.075 --> 03:36.388
To think about,
much less emphasize,

03:36.423 --> 03:37.700
with somebody who comes from

03:37.734 --> 03:39.633
five generations of coal miners

03:39.667 --> 03:41.807
in a place that looks like this

03:41.842 --> 03:44.879
is, to our enduring shame,
unthinkable.

03:44.914 --> 03:47.261
Why can't these coal miners
get retrained?

03:47.296 --> 03:50.091
Maybe put up solar panels
for a living.

03:50.126 --> 03:52.887
Why would these conservative,
deeply religious people

03:52.922 --> 03:56.477
vote for a thrice married
billionaire New Yorker?

03:56.512 --> 04:02.276
Well, I went to West Virginia
and, you know what, screw you.

04:04.036 --> 04:06.107
Here, in the heart
of every belief system

04:06.142 --> 04:08.109
I've ever mocked
or fought against,

04:08.144 --> 04:10.974
I was welcomed with
open arms by everyone.

04:11.009 --> 04:14.806
I found a place both
heartbreaking and beautiful,

04:14.840 --> 04:18.913
a place that symbolizes
and contains everything wrong

04:18.947 --> 04:23.470
and everything wonderful
and hopeful about America.

04:26.231 --> 04:27.750
The town of Welch,

04:27.784 --> 04:30.994
known in its glory days
as little New York.

04:31.029 --> 04:31.529
♪

04:37.829 --> 04:39.589
Welch is a very rural area.

04:39.624 --> 04:43.110
I mean, it's an hour
away from Walmart,

04:43.144 --> 04:45.215
I mean, if that
tells you anything.

04:45.250 --> 04:48.978
It's a real old, historic
town built in the 1800s.

04:49.012 --> 04:51.325
The American dream in miniature.

04:51.360 --> 04:54.535
A place where generations
of immigrants and dreamers

04:54.570 --> 04:56.882
could work
and lift up their family.

04:56.917 --> 04:59.540
The town of Welch,
when it was booming,

04:59.575 --> 05:01.853
the sidewalks were so crowded

05:01.887 --> 05:05.166
there would be traffic
backed up, like, a mile.

05:05.201 --> 05:08.238
You couldn't find
a place to park.

05:08.273 --> 05:12.035
We had three hospitals,
had the taxicab stand,

05:12.070 --> 05:14.659
had, like, three jewelry stores.

05:14.693 --> 05:16.488
It was just a wonderful place.

05:16.523 --> 05:18.801
The rest of the country
took a lot of money

05:18.835 --> 05:21.044
out of these hills
over the decades,

05:21.079 --> 05:23.702
billions and billions
of dollars,

05:23.737 --> 05:25.635
and when it became cheaper
or more convenient

05:25.670 --> 05:28.845
to pull the coal we needed
to power our electrical grids

05:28.880 --> 05:31.883
and to make our steel elsewhere,

05:31.917 --> 05:34.126
this is what was left behind.

05:38.130 --> 05:40.409
But this is not
a poverty porn show.

05:40.443 --> 05:42.272
Do not pity the people here,

05:42.307 --> 05:43.929
who, despite what you may think,

05:43.964 --> 05:46.932
are not unrealistic
about a return

05:46.967 --> 05:49.728
to the glory days of coal
and better times.

05:49.763 --> 05:52.179
I drank coffee from the time
I could walk.

05:52.213 --> 05:55.078
They put coffee in your bottle,
coffee or wine.

05:56.977 --> 05:59.393
Linda McKinney is a true
daughter of Appalachia.

05:59.428 --> 06:01.119
She raised her children here.

06:01.153 --> 06:02.879
Linda's husband, Bob McKinney,

06:02.914 --> 06:05.123
is a longtime
mine safety inspector.

06:05.157 --> 06:07.263
Now, your family's
originally from Naples?

06:07.297 --> 06:09.299
Is that right? Naples area?
Yes. Yes.

06:09.334 --> 06:11.232
Came here in 1923

06:11.267 --> 06:12.779
trying to strike it rich
in the coal mines.

06:12.786 --> 06:15.616
My mother died when I was five,

06:15.651 --> 06:17.515
so we went to live
with my nonna,

06:17.549 --> 06:18.895
and the first day I was there,

06:18.930 --> 06:20.690
she pulled me up
to a cook stove.

06:20.725 --> 06:23.037
This is the dish
that my nonna cooked

06:23.072 --> 06:25.971
during hunting season
with squirrels.

06:26.006 --> 06:29.699
These aren't squirrels.
This is chicken.

06:29.734 --> 06:31.977
Dinner is a not untypical
expression

06:32.012 --> 06:34.635
of hardscrabble
Appalachian practicality...

06:34.670 --> 06:36.810
Now, I don't measure anything,

06:36.844 --> 06:38.467
so nothing has a recipe here.

06:38.501 --> 06:40.469
- And Neapolitan roots.
- Basil.

06:40.503 --> 06:43.644
Home kitchen gardens,
hunting, and gathering.

06:43.679 --> 06:46.440
This my dad would call
piselles; it's peas.

06:46.475 --> 06:48.338
Ooh, making mama dance.

06:50.824 --> 06:53.585
Now, this is what I'm famous
for in these parts.

06:53.620 --> 06:55.587
Have you ever had
spaghetti pizza?

06:55.622 --> 06:56.588
- Wow.
- No, you haven't.

06:56.623 --> 06:57.624
Don't say you have.

07:00.868 --> 07:02.594
The tomato sauce was made

07:02.629 --> 07:04.665
with Joel's tomatoes
at the food bank.

07:04.700 --> 07:06.253
We harvested those yesterday,

07:06.287 --> 07:07.944
and I made spaghetti sauce.
Wow.

07:07.979 --> 07:10.360
Nearby, Joel runs an organic

07:10.395 --> 07:13.605
hydroponic farm that supplies
the local school system.

07:17.229 --> 07:18.990
The people here are very good.

07:19.024 --> 07:20.750
They'd give you the shirt
off their back,

07:20.785 --> 07:24.961
come together in times
of tragedy or anything.

07:24.996 --> 07:27.274
Christian values mean
something here.

07:27.308 --> 07:30.035
They're practiced
on the street and in the home.

07:30.070 --> 07:33.349
Most of you have all got
your potatoes, right?

07:33.383 --> 07:36.007
Linda runs Five Loaves
and Two Fishes,

07:36.041 --> 07:37.836
a food bank that holds
many of the lives here

07:37.871 --> 07:40.218
together during tough times.

07:40.252 --> 07:43.842
16,000 people walk through
these doors annually

07:43.877 --> 07:46.155
in a county of 20,000.

07:46.189 --> 07:48.813
Gracious God, we just
thank you for this day

07:48.847 --> 07:50.711
that we're able to
give food out again.

07:50.746 --> 07:52.817
This is not a regular give out.

07:52.851 --> 07:54.784
Watch over us. Protect us.

07:54.819 --> 07:57.304
Help us to keep cool heads.

08:00.341 --> 08:00.841
♪

08:04.656 --> 08:06.727
Father, we pray over
the food we're about to eat

08:06.762 --> 08:08.211
for the nourishment of our body.

08:08.246 --> 08:09.972
Just bless it
in the name of Christ.

08:10.006 --> 08:12.146
- Amen.
- Amen.

08:12.181 --> 08:12.681
♪

08:16.392 --> 08:18.843
This is our home.
We love it here.

08:18.877 --> 08:20.430
We're very close to our church.

08:20.465 --> 08:21.535
Everybody knows everybody.

08:21.570 --> 08:23.019
They're all dying now,

08:23.054 --> 08:24.883
but we're still hanging on,
aren't we, honey?

08:24.918 --> 08:26.920
Yeah.

08:26.954 --> 08:28.542
Was there any sizable

08:28.577 --> 08:30.544
Italian-American community
here at some time?

08:30.579 --> 08:32.270
Oh, yes. Oh, yes.

08:32.304 --> 08:34.755
A lot of immigrants from
different countries came here.

08:34.789 --> 08:36.446
- Still? How large?
- No.

08:36.481 --> 08:38.034
We've gone from what,
100,000 to 10,000.

08:38.068 --> 08:39.587
100,000 down to about
10,000-12,000.

08:39.621 --> 08:42.693
In the county itself,
as of the last census, so.

08:42.729 --> 08:44.696
Those are some grim statistics.

08:44.731 --> 08:46.456
Yes, yes.

08:46.491 --> 08:50.012
The coal that came out of
this area built America, right?

08:50.046 --> 08:51.185
Yes.

08:51.220 --> 08:52.490
McDowell County alone was called

08:52.497 --> 08:54.016
a billion-dollar coal field,

08:54.050 --> 08:57.226
and the people that were
in charge at the time

08:57.260 --> 08:59.918
didn't take advantage
of all that money

08:59.953 --> 09:02.472
in case something did happen
to the coal mine.

09:02.507 --> 09:04.854
The cool thing is that West
Virginia's developing

09:04.889 --> 09:07.961
a strong entrepreneur movement

09:07.995 --> 09:09.928
that a lot of people
don't know about.

09:09.963 --> 09:12.448
Like with Joe, he started
a hydroponic growing.

09:12.482 --> 09:14.726
I mean, not blaming others
for their problems,

09:14.761 --> 09:16.486
just trying to solve their own.

09:16.521 --> 09:19.420
A lot of people that's
really doing a lot of good

09:19.455 --> 09:21.491
that we don't hear about.

09:21.526 --> 09:22.907
This is our pumpkin pie cake.

09:22.941 --> 09:24.633
Have you ever had
a pumpkin pie cake?

09:24.667 --> 09:27.394
You probably won't like it,
so we'll take your spot.

09:29.189 --> 09:32.951
We got spoiled. The last
coal mines I worked at, I made-

09:32.986 --> 09:36.299
base salary was $94,000 a year.

09:36.334 --> 09:38.060
I also taught vocational school,

09:38.094 --> 09:39.751
and most of the kids
that I had said,

09:39.786 --> 09:40.959
"Well, I don't need this.

09:40.994 --> 09:42.271
I'm gonna go in the coal
mines."

09:42.305 --> 09:44.169
There's just
an education piece there

09:44.204 --> 09:46.344
now that we're trying to
instill in some of the people

09:46.378 --> 09:49.658
that still have that mentality
that coal was king,

09:49.692 --> 09:51.660
and, you know,
we don't doubt that,

09:51.694 --> 09:55.525
but we try to think outside the
box and look at some other...

09:55.560 --> 09:58.149
Some other opportunities
that might be there.

10:01.152 --> 10:02.671
The job that I have right now

10:02.705 --> 10:04.534
is probably one of
the best jobs around here

10:04.569 --> 10:08.677
other than the few guys
that works at the coal mines.

10:08.711 --> 10:10.851
I operate this school bus.

10:13.889 --> 10:16.132
♪

10:16.167 --> 10:19.653
I mentioned God,
and guns, and Trump.

10:19.688 --> 10:20.861
Get more physical!

10:20.896 --> 10:23.105
Let's go. Run!

10:23.139 --> 10:26.384
- But I forgot another
big one: football.

10:26.418 --> 10:29.318
I was born and raised here.
I've been here all my life.

10:29.352 --> 10:30.899
Played defensive end
for Welch High School.

10:30.906 --> 10:33.149
Graduated there in 1976.

10:33.184 --> 10:35.324
The Mountview Golden Knights
have long carried

10:35.358 --> 10:38.223
the mantle of the town
as perpetual underdogs.

10:38.258 --> 10:40.501
Mostly the children of miners,

10:40.536 --> 10:43.056
many from very difficult
situations at home.

10:43.090 --> 10:45.058
Why you walking? Hurry up!

10:45.092 --> 10:46.473
This week, it's homecoming.

10:46.507 --> 10:47.957
Whistle!

10:47.992 --> 10:49.683
Coach Larry Thomson
has, of late,

10:49.718 --> 10:52.410
imposed some order
and higher academic standards

10:52.444 --> 10:53.687
on the Knights.

10:53.722 --> 10:55.689
There are high hopes.

10:55.724 --> 10:57.415
♪

10:57.449 --> 10:58.927
Lord, thank you for this
food we're about to receive

10:58.934 --> 11:00.418
for the nourishment
of our bodies,

11:00.452 --> 11:02.385
and bless these young men
and these young women

11:02.420 --> 11:03.863
as they cheer
and as they play on the field.

11:03.870 --> 11:05.699
In Jesus name I pray, amen.

11:05.734 --> 11:07.874
Amen.

11:07.908 --> 11:09.565
Let's go eat, man.

11:09.599 --> 11:11.981
Local boosters put together
a pregame meal

11:12.016 --> 11:14.432
of ribs, baked potatoes,
and chicken.

11:14.466 --> 11:16.047
These kids, you know,
they got long days.

11:16.054 --> 11:18.919
They wake up 4:45 or 5:00,

11:18.954 --> 11:20.120
and they don't leave
off the hill with us

11:20.127 --> 11:21.715
until about 7:00
after practice,

11:21.750 --> 11:23.268
so, no, they go through a lot.

11:23.303 --> 11:26.755
How many generations of coal
in your family?

11:26.789 --> 11:29.033
- At least five.
- Wow.

11:29.067 --> 11:31.587
Coach Mike Anderson
is second in command.

11:31.621 --> 11:35.384
Coal in anybody else's family?
Yeah?

11:35.418 --> 11:38.870
Like, trash man, that's
a real common job in my family.

11:38.905 --> 11:40.354
Don't feel bad; trash men

11:40.389 --> 11:42.425
make more money
than teachers do, Chavo.

11:43.806 --> 11:45.635
Fred "Fatback" Minko,

11:45.670 --> 11:47.223
Micah "Woody" McLaughlin,

11:47.258 --> 11:48.742
and Cole "Chavo" Anderson

11:48.777 --> 11:51.124
are in many ways
typical Mountview players

11:51.158 --> 11:53.091
and students
with the hopes and dreams

11:53.126 --> 11:55.645
of, well, any other
high school students.

11:55.680 --> 11:56.957
Homecoming.
It is.

11:56.992 --> 11:58.492
How big a deal
is football in general,

11:58.510 --> 12:02.135
and this game,
and what you guys do?

12:02.169 --> 12:03.785
You know, a lot of these
kids, they understand

12:03.792 --> 12:05.269
that there's not
a lot of resources here,

12:05.276 --> 12:07.312
and before, you can kind
of feel the dreariness

12:07.347 --> 12:09.590
that kind of lingered
around the community,

12:09.625 --> 12:11.316
but now, you know,
with these boys winning,

12:11.351 --> 12:13.042
with the worth ethic
they're putting in,

12:13.077 --> 12:14.768
you can feel
the support, you know?

12:14.803 --> 12:16.936
Like, we did a few community
outreach programs this summer.

12:16.943 --> 12:18.834
They went down to the park and
they painted, and they feel it.

12:18.841 --> 12:20.740
They feel that sense of pride.

12:20.774 --> 12:23.604
How has this football program
changed your life?

12:23.639 --> 12:25.496
It gives me something to do,
stay out of trouble.

12:25.503 --> 12:28.506
Some of these guys
have changed 100%.

12:28.540 --> 12:31.267
They had no guidance,
no discipline.

12:31.302 --> 12:33.683
They have outside forces
that could be pulling them

12:33.718 --> 12:35.271
into different directions,

12:35.306 --> 12:38.516
and they know how that life
is gonna go for them,

12:38.550 --> 12:42.520
and as a team in here
relying on each other,

12:42.554 --> 12:46.110
their limits
are out of this world.

12:46.144 --> 12:48.250
Now, in the past, you could
get out of high school,

12:48.284 --> 12:50.183
pretty sure that
you were to make big money

12:50.217 --> 12:52.185
in... you know, working in coal.

12:52.219 --> 12:54.256
You don't have that
kind of guarantee now.

12:54.290 --> 12:56.189
What do you see yourself
doing in ten years?

12:56.223 --> 12:58.847
- Journalism.
- Journalism.

12:58.881 --> 13:01.781
I hope in ten years,
I hope to be studying my PhD

13:01.815 --> 13:03.023
and be a mechanical engineer.

13:03.058 --> 13:04.680
- Mechanical engineer.
- Yes, sir.

13:04.714 --> 13:06.364
I'm definitely gonna be
a neuro psychologist.

13:06.371 --> 13:08.097
- Neuro psychologist?
- Yep.

13:08.132 --> 13:11.135
You know, what's tougher,
life or football?

13:11.169 --> 13:13.171
- Life.
- Life, definitely.

13:13.206 --> 13:15.035
There's no halftime in life.

13:15.070 --> 13:16.726
There's no time outs in life.

13:16.761 --> 13:18.452
There's no none of that.

13:18.487 --> 13:20.558
That was a really good answer.

13:22.249 --> 13:23.975
"Love thy brother" is one thing.

13:24.010 --> 13:27.807
That's all well and good,
but these guys want to win.

13:27.841 --> 13:30.740
They need to win,
and everyone will be watching.

13:30.775 --> 13:35.193
♪ I make my home
in mountain people ♪

13:35.228 --> 13:36.954
Why are you dancing with them?

13:36.988 --> 13:39.819
♪ My spirit flowing

13:39.853 --> 13:41.890
♪ Through their veins

13:41.924 --> 13:44.306
♪ My soul will live
with them forever ♪

13:44.340 --> 13:46.826
- One, two, three.
- Family!

13:46.860 --> 13:47.965
♪

13:47.999 --> 13:54.488
♪ Appalachia is my name

13:54.523 --> 13:55.023
♪

14:19.030 --> 14:20.998
You're a badass.

14:23.310 --> 14:25.623
Did you really just say that?

14:27.142 --> 14:32.595
Them boys say West Virginia
girls are gold diggers.

14:32.630 --> 14:36.289
Them boys should know better,
because in West Virginia,

14:36.323 --> 14:41.397
there ain't no gold,
just black, black coal.

14:45.677 --> 14:48.301
And them girls,
them West Virginia girls

14:48.335 --> 14:50.096
don't take no handouts.

14:50.130 --> 14:55.618
They got a living to make,
and stripping is hard work.

14:55.653 --> 14:57.034
♪

14:57.068 --> 14:58.799
West Virginia was settled
by people who were

14:58.828 --> 15:02.763
fleeing persecution,
by homesteaders,

15:02.798 --> 15:07.389
people who just wanted to live
their lives their own way,

15:07.423 --> 15:09.253
but the discovery
of vast coal reserves

15:09.287 --> 15:11.841
and the big business
that grew up around it

15:11.876 --> 15:13.843
changed everything.

15:13.878 --> 15:16.260
Boom, boom.

15:16.294 --> 15:18.745
Them girls shake it.

15:18.779 --> 15:20.160
Boom, boom.

15:20.195 --> 15:21.990
Them girls dance.

15:22.024 --> 15:23.681
♪

15:23.715 --> 15:25.855
Them boys know some
of them West Virginia girls

15:25.890 --> 15:27.857
can't count, so they laugh

15:27.892 --> 15:30.757
and call them names
like crazy, like whore,

15:30.791 --> 15:34.416
just after they take
all their mineral rights.

15:34.450 --> 15:39.007
Boom, boom. She was wrong.

15:39.041 --> 15:42.665
Boom, boom. Forever gone.

15:42.700 --> 15:45.703
Boom, boom.

15:45.737 --> 15:47.705
Them boys,

15:47.739 --> 15:50.639
them girls,

15:50.673 --> 15:53.607
them mountains,

15:53.642 --> 15:55.644
explode.

16:03.238 --> 16:03.738
♪

16:14.663 --> 16:17.286
What is right, what is wrong,

16:17.321 --> 16:18.391
what is mine,

16:18.425 --> 16:21.152
and what gets taken away.

16:21.187 --> 16:24.397
The town of War understands
this dynamic well.

16:24.431 --> 16:26.502
It's a former coal
and timber camp

16:26.537 --> 16:28.297
that has more than
paid its dues.

16:28.332 --> 16:30.368
You can't go wrong
with biscuits and gravy.

16:30.403 --> 16:32.060
Works for me.
Biscuits, gravy,

16:32.094 --> 16:34.131
two eggs up, and a coffee.

16:34.165 --> 16:36.202
I'm a happy man.
Yeah.

16:36.236 --> 16:38.480
The War Café is one of the few

16:38.514 --> 16:40.758
family owned businesses
left in town.

16:40.792 --> 16:44.520
♪

16:44.555 --> 16:47.316
It's an obvious
"New Yorker arrives in town"

16:47.351 --> 16:49.767
first question:
why no cell service?

16:49.801 --> 16:53.357
I've been to the farthest
regions of the Arabian desert.

16:53.391 --> 16:55.559
All I got to do is climb a
dune, I'm gonna get three bars.

16:55.566 --> 16:57.740
I mean, the mountains,
it's hard to get signals

16:57.775 --> 16:59.673
down into each individual
valley.

16:59.708 --> 17:02.435
Nick Mullins is a former
coal miner turned writer,

17:02.469 --> 17:04.608
working in public outreach
trying to help people

17:04.644 --> 17:07.095
transition away
from fossil fuel.

17:07.128 --> 17:10.063
Try calling an ambulance here
and getting out of the county

17:10.098 --> 17:11.616
to the closest hospital.

17:11.651 --> 17:12.990
They don't deliver babies
at the hospital

17:12.997 --> 17:14.273
in this county anymore.

17:14.309 --> 17:15.896
Elaine McMillan Sheldon

17:15.931 --> 17:18.278
is an Oscar nominated
documentary filmmaker,

17:18.313 --> 17:20.798
born and raised in
Southern West Virginia.

17:20.832 --> 17:23.249
If you were describing
this area...

17:23.282 --> 17:25.527
Church going,
it's a great part religious,

17:25.560 --> 17:26.976
gun rights, important.

17:27.011 --> 17:28.288
A lot of people of my ilk,

17:28.323 --> 17:30.083
that's not gonna resonate
at all.

17:30.118 --> 17:31.636
In fact, it sounds threatening.

17:31.671 --> 17:33.286
Right, but both sides
are saying the same thing.

17:33.293 --> 17:35.744
Both sides feel threatened
by each other.

17:35.778 --> 17:37.228
- Right.
- And I would say a majority

17:37.263 --> 17:39.299
of people that live
in this region

17:39.334 --> 17:40.438
want to be left alone.

17:40.473 --> 17:41.819
The traditions of this place,

17:41.853 --> 17:43.331
the things that we value,
whether that be

17:43.338 --> 17:45.823
family, interpersonal
communication,

17:45.857 --> 17:47.665
not having cell phone
technology to distract us,

17:47.687 --> 17:50.655
those type of things
sort of butt up against

17:50.690 --> 17:52.243
America's idea of progress,

17:52.278 --> 17:54.211
and it's why we've always
been looked at

17:54.245 --> 17:56.005
as being backwards.

17:59.043 --> 17:59.543
♪

18:04.704 --> 18:07.086
Being part of the media
but living here

18:07.120 --> 18:08.501
is a really big challenge

18:08.535 --> 18:11.262
because rarely
people like myself

18:11.297 --> 18:13.299
actually are the ones
that control our narrative,

18:13.333 --> 18:15.301
that control our story.

18:17.165 --> 18:21.514
It was always too easy
to come gawk at West Virginia,

18:21.548 --> 18:23.032
to make it the poster child

18:23.067 --> 18:25.690
for whatever the agenda
of the moment was.

18:25.725 --> 18:30.764
Lazy depictions of
stereotypical West Virginians,

18:30.799 --> 18:34.113
hillbillies and hicks
tucked into isolated hollers

18:34.147 --> 18:37.806
to be pitied or made objects
of laughter and derision.

18:37.840 --> 18:40.533
If you Google Appalachia,
to this day,

18:40.567 --> 18:43.052
you're gonna see
dirty faced kids,

18:43.087 --> 18:44.951
barefoot on a front porch,

18:44.985 --> 18:46.953
shaking Lyndon B. Johnson's
hand.

18:46.987 --> 18:49.714
There's a lot more
to Appalachia than that.

18:50.750 --> 18:54.512
In 1964, Lyndon Johnson
declared his War on Poverty.

18:54.547 --> 18:57.170
A good thing, yes?

18:57.205 --> 19:00.553
But the accompanying press
tour portraying people here

19:00.587 --> 19:02.348
as an incapable and bewildered,

19:02.382 --> 19:06.904
helpless mass missed
the basic essential character,

19:06.938 --> 19:09.631
the pride,
and the self-reliant core

19:09.665 --> 19:11.011
of the people here.

19:11.046 --> 19:12.737
That damage is lasting.

19:12.772 --> 19:15.671
When you come in and keep
telling us how poor, fat,

19:15.706 --> 19:17.466
how all these things are,

19:17.501 --> 19:19.503
I think we've all felt it
at some point: shame.

19:19.537 --> 19:22.920
What should people know about
this area that they don't know,

19:22.954 --> 19:24.853
that they're not getting?

19:24.887 --> 19:26.406
Well, I think it's been said,

19:26.441 --> 19:28.305
but it's just not been hit home.

19:28.339 --> 19:31.653
It's just how much that people

19:31.687 --> 19:34.173
in this area
have been exploited.

19:40.040 --> 19:41.387
♪

19:41.421 --> 19:42.836
The land agents who came in

19:42.871 --> 19:46.254
and bought up
all the mineral rights.

19:46.288 --> 19:48.739
The coal and timber companies
that started extracting

19:48.773 --> 19:50.112
and taking everybody's
labor rights.

19:50.119 --> 19:52.363
I can't fight a big
coal company.

19:52.398 --> 19:54.331
It's got too much money.

19:54.365 --> 19:55.849
Politicians from D.C.

19:55.884 --> 19:57.610
that could make a quick
day trip down here

19:57.644 --> 19:59.128
and get a good sound bite.

19:59.163 --> 20:01.441
Who is a miner in this group?
Who is it?

20:01.476 --> 20:04.927
Stand up.
You're all standing up anyway.

20:04.962 --> 20:07.136
- The drug companies.
- 9 million pills

20:07.171 --> 20:08.931
in Kermit, West Virginia
over two years.

20:08.966 --> 20:10.416
One pharmacy, 9 million pills.

20:10.450 --> 20:12.866
One pharmacy in a town
of 372 people.

20:12.901 --> 20:14.937
There's some political
figures that come through

20:14.972 --> 20:16.173
and say that they will
try to get away

20:16.180 --> 20:18.217
from the mono economy of coal.

20:18.251 --> 20:20.771
The great issue confronting
West Virginia in 1960

20:20.805 --> 20:22.290
is economic development.

20:22.324 --> 20:23.636
But by and large,

20:23.670 --> 20:25.154
the industry doesn't
really want that.

20:25.189 --> 20:26.811
Why would they?

20:26.846 --> 20:28.392
If somebody can live here
and make a similar living wage

20:28.399 --> 20:30.056
and not have to risk their life,

20:30.090 --> 20:31.644
then they're not going to.

20:31.678 --> 20:34.785
The other side of this is that
Democrats, they don't take

20:34.819 --> 20:36.925
a lot of time to understand the problems here.

20:36.959 --> 20:39.721
I just want to know
how you can say

20:39.755 --> 20:42.724
you're gonna put a lot
of coal miners out of jobs,

20:42.758 --> 20:44.657
and then come in here
and tell us

20:44.691 --> 20:46.003
how you're gonna be our friend.

20:46.037 --> 20:47.487
I don't think people understand

20:47.522 --> 20:48.833
just how genuine and wonderful

20:48.868 --> 20:50.421
the people are
in these mountains,

20:50.456 --> 20:52.458
people who have just
worked all their lives

20:52.492 --> 20:56.496
and who've sacrificed so much
for their families.

20:59.534 --> 21:01.018
♪

21:01.052 --> 21:02.571
You cannot talk
about West Virginia

21:02.606 --> 21:04.780
without talking about coal,

21:04.815 --> 21:07.990
and coal is
a complex issue here,

21:08.025 --> 21:11.304
tied into the cell tissue and
the family pride of the people

21:11.339 --> 21:15.274
who have worked
in the mines for generations.

21:15.308 --> 21:17.690
♪

21:17.724 --> 21:20.209
Yeah, man, that coal mines
is something else,

21:20.244 --> 21:23.005
you know, boy, you got to take
care of yourself in there.

21:23.040 --> 21:26.699
That fan is blowing about
200,000 cubic feet of air

21:26.733 --> 21:29.218
into the mine... fresh air.

21:29.253 --> 21:31.048
When you go in that mine,
you don't know

21:31.082 --> 21:33.533
whether you're gonna live
to see the outside again.

21:33.568 --> 21:34.068
♪

21:53.035 --> 21:57.488
Today we're going
about 5,000 feet.

21:57.523 --> 21:59.248
5,000 feet deep?

21:59.283 --> 22:03.632
Yeah, oh, yeah.

22:03.667 --> 22:06.739
It's a little
bumpy ride in places.

22:06.773 --> 22:08.741
Pat Graham is the foreman

22:08.775 --> 22:10.570
at the Pay Car mine in Kimball.

22:10.605 --> 22:12.469
Watch your head.

22:12.503 --> 22:13.003
♪

22:16.783 --> 22:20.511
This particular mine
is a metallurgical break hole.

22:20.546 --> 22:22.133
- So this is full of steel?
- Yes.

22:23.618 --> 22:27.242
The average wage of a miner
is 60% greater

22:27.276 --> 22:30.418
than the average wage of all
laborers in the United States.

22:30.452 --> 22:31.936
- Wow.
- That's pretty phenomenal.

22:31.971 --> 22:35.181
It's easy to see why people
in McDowell County

22:35.215 --> 22:36.769
want mining jobs.

22:44.293 --> 22:45.571
♪

22:45.605 --> 22:47.780
I was staying in a town
nearby, Welch.

22:47.814 --> 22:49.402
There's no bar.

22:56.305 --> 22:57.928
Wow.

22:57.962 --> 23:00.102
Heavenly Father, we'd like
to gather here to thank you

23:00.137 --> 23:02.691
for this opportunity
to support our families.

23:02.726 --> 23:04.244
Please watch after us
and keep us safe

23:04.279 --> 23:06.557
while we're underground
working. Amen.

23:06.592 --> 23:08.594
Amen.

23:08.628 --> 23:10.112
♪

23:10.147 --> 23:12.632
- What do you got?
- Bear meat and chicken.

23:12.667 --> 23:14.220
Oh, damn.

23:14.254 --> 23:15.877
I may just put my sandwich
back here

23:15.911 --> 23:17.741
if you got bear meat.

23:17.775 --> 23:19.225
♪

23:19.259 --> 23:20.882
That's delicious.

23:20.916 --> 23:22.297
Do you think the country
as a whole,

23:22.331 --> 23:23.988
do you think they understand

23:24.023 --> 23:26.474
the coal business at all,
what coal mining's about?

23:26.508 --> 23:27.889
- No.
- No.

23:27.923 --> 23:29.331
They don't really
understand at all.

23:29.338 --> 23:30.961
When you travel
from New York to here,

23:30.995 --> 23:32.618
whether you're on a boat,
plane, train,

23:32.652 --> 23:33.853
or in the sky
or driving on a car,

23:33.860 --> 23:35.483
it's because of a mine.

23:35.517 --> 23:38.934
Mining causes damage
to the environment.

23:38.969 --> 23:41.281
Of this there is no doubt,

23:41.316 --> 23:44.077
but what cannot be grown
must be mined.

23:44.112 --> 23:46.355
There ain't no cell phones,
for instance,

23:46.390 --> 23:48.357
without mines somewhere.

23:48.392 --> 23:50.946
Does anybody think
it's gonna come back big time,

23:50.981 --> 23:52.465
like 30 years ago or...

23:52.500 --> 23:55.192
My personal opinion,
every time a Republican

23:55.226 --> 23:56.745
is in there, it goes up.

23:58.471 --> 24:01.267
This used to be a solidly
democratic state.

24:01.301 --> 24:03.131
What do you think
made Trump attractive:

24:03.165 --> 24:05.858
a city slicker,
three times married?

24:05.892 --> 24:08.032
- That's easy for me.
- Yeah.

24:08.067 --> 24:10.828
Hillary shows up here,
and she openly said

24:10.863 --> 24:13.831
she's gonna put a lot
of coal miners out of work.

24:15.419 --> 24:16.938
Wrong answer.

24:16.972 --> 24:18.387
How many kids you got?

24:18.422 --> 24:19.630
- I got three.
- Three?

24:19.665 --> 24:21.390
- Six.
- Four.

24:21.425 --> 24:23.358
If you saw your kids
had other options,

24:23.392 --> 24:26.188
would you recommend that
they join the family business?

24:26.223 --> 24:28.674
- No, sir, no.
- You would say no.

24:28.708 --> 24:30.676
I would about guarantee
if everybody here,

24:30.710 --> 24:32.332
their dad who worked
in the coal mines

24:32.367 --> 24:34.852
probably told their son,
"Don't go into the coal mines."

24:34.887 --> 24:37.648
- That's what I was told.
- That's what I told mine.

24:37.683 --> 24:38.891
- Yeah.
- I mean, you're gonna

24:38.925 --> 24:40.375
tell them, "No, don't do it,"

24:40.409 --> 24:42.515
but you know, if they do,
you're gonna be proud.

24:42.550 --> 24:43.861
I'm proud.

24:43.896 --> 24:45.200
From the stickers
we put on our buckets,

24:45.207 --> 24:47.658
from the stickers
we put on our hats,

24:47.693 --> 24:49.660
to my coffee mug there,
passed down.

24:49.695 --> 24:52.352
I don't mess that thing up,
my son goes into the mines,

24:52.387 --> 24:54.251
that's gonna be his.

24:54.285 --> 24:56.667
When and if you retire,
what would you like to do?

24:56.702 --> 24:58.048
Where would you like to go?

25:07.782 --> 25:08.282
♪

25:27.491 --> 25:30.080
♪ I'm a stone's
throw from the mill ♪

25:30.114 --> 25:33.566
♪ And I'm a good walk
to the river ♪

25:33.601 --> 25:36.293
♪ But my working day is over

25:36.327 --> 25:39.434
♪ We'll go swim
our cares away ♪

25:39.468 --> 25:43.680
It's so easy from afar
to say that coal's time here

25:43.714 --> 25:45.889
has come and gone,

25:45.923 --> 25:49.271
that we should let the miners
move, find some other work.

25:49.306 --> 25:50.618
What other work?

25:50.652 --> 25:53.413
This state's biggest employer
is now Walmart.

25:53.448 --> 25:56.416
♪ I've seen my share
of trouble ♪

25:56.451 --> 26:00.559
♪ And I've held
my weight in shame ♪

26:00.593 --> 26:05.460
♪ But I'm baptized
in your name ♪

26:05.494 --> 26:07.255
♪ Lovely Lady May

26:07.289 --> 26:10.430
Whatever your views,
respect these people,

26:10.465 --> 26:14.055
what they do
and what they've paid.

26:14.089 --> 26:15.090
Ladies and gentlemen...

26:35.283 --> 26:35.783
♪

26:40.495 --> 26:43.532
Ready, set, go!

26:52.576 --> 26:54.371
♪

26:54.405 --> 26:57.857
♪ Early in the morning
when the sun does rise ♪

26:57.892 --> 27:00.377
♪

27:00.411 --> 27:03.518
♪ Laying in the bed
with bloodshot eyes ♪

27:03.552 --> 27:06.038
♪

27:06.072 --> 27:09.213
♪ Run me ragged
but I don't fret ♪

27:09.248 --> 27:11.388
♪

27:11.422 --> 27:14.771
♪ Cause there ain't been one
slow me down none yet ♪

27:17.187 --> 27:20.224
♪ Get me drinking
that moonshine ♪

27:20.259 --> 27:22.882
♪ Get me higher
than the grocery bill ♪

27:22.917 --> 27:25.298
♪ Take my troubles
to the high wall ♪

27:25.333 --> 27:28.474
♪ Throw them in the river
and get your fill ♪

27:28.508 --> 27:30.856
♪ Lord it's a mighty
hard living ♪

27:30.890 --> 27:34.411
♪ But it's damn good feeling
to run these roads ♪

27:34.445 --> 27:37.586
So these things have to be
durable, to say the least?

27:37.621 --> 27:39.519
I mean, you're pounding
the hell out of them.

27:39.554 --> 27:41.418
They're actually built
to be indestructible.

27:41.452 --> 27:43.489
- Indestructible.
- Yeah, that's the plan.

27:43.523 --> 27:45.180
♪

27:45.215 --> 27:47.700
Yeah!

27:47.735 --> 27:49.806
Well, I guess we broke it.

27:51.255 --> 27:53.050
This bat-shit crazy, vertical,

27:53.085 --> 27:55.708
Mad Max drag race
come demolition derby

27:55.743 --> 27:58.090
is called rock bouncing.

27:58.124 --> 27:59.850
Keep my neck from
bouncing around too much?

27:59.885 --> 28:01.749
Yeah, and what they're
actually designed for

28:01.783 --> 28:03.336
is major collisions,

28:03.371 --> 28:05.822
and it keeps your head
from tearing off your body.

28:05.856 --> 28:08.894
Adam Ringer is a native son,
jack of many trades,

28:08.928 --> 28:10.619
and a man who's all too happy

28:10.654 --> 28:12.863
to spend the day
trashing some hills

28:12.898 --> 28:14.382
just to show me a good time.

28:14.416 --> 28:17.178
♪ Get me drinking
that moonshine ♪

28:17.212 --> 28:20.181
♪ Get me higher
than the grocery bill ♪

28:20.215 --> 28:22.873
♪ Lord it's a mighty hard
living ♪

28:22.908 --> 28:25.945
♪ But a damn good feeling
to run these roads ♪

28:25.980 --> 28:27.464
♪

28:27.498 --> 28:30.467
- So that was pretty badass.
- Yeah.

28:30.501 --> 28:32.780
♪

28:35.817 --> 28:39.718
♪

28:39.752 --> 28:43.894
All right, you got your
frog legs, turtle patties.

28:43.929 --> 28:45.724
Eric Williams
is a hunter and trapper

28:45.758 --> 28:47.380
who caught most of this meal

28:47.415 --> 28:50.314
wading waist deep
in the swamp on his property.

28:50.349 --> 28:52.661
- You ever ate snapping turtle?
- Oh, I'm definite...

28:52.696 --> 28:54.215
I'm not missing that.

28:54.249 --> 28:57.977
Small mouth bass, catfish,
barbecued and fried.

28:58.012 --> 28:59.668
Wow, what a spread.

28:59.703 --> 29:03.120
♪

29:03.155 --> 29:05.433
Trail riding ATVs, off-roading,

29:05.467 --> 29:07.331
and the supporting industries

29:07.366 --> 29:09.678
are an up-and-coming play
for tourism in this state.

29:09.713 --> 29:11.784
There are thousands
of miles of trails

29:11.819 --> 29:14.960
running through the hills
in places like this.

29:14.994 --> 29:17.065
Anybody with any off-road
vehicle can come:

29:17.100 --> 29:19.240
dirt bikes, four wheelers,
mega trucks.

29:19.274 --> 29:21.242
King Knob Motorsports Park,

29:21.276 --> 29:23.692
owned by Mike Hanson
and Amber Williams.

29:23.727 --> 29:26.109
Do they have to sign
a release before they come on?

29:26.143 --> 29:27.524
- They do.
- Yeah, that's smart.

29:27.558 --> 29:28.628
Yeah.

29:28.663 --> 29:30.285
We actually climb stuff
that's vertical.

29:30.320 --> 29:32.011
- Straight up?
- Yep.

29:32.046 --> 29:34.842
Yeah, this race this weekend,
the last 30 feet of the hill,

29:34.876 --> 29:36.844
the second hill,
was actually vertical.

29:36.878 --> 29:38.217
You had to hit it
with enough momentum

29:38.224 --> 29:39.218
to skip up over it
and land on top.

29:39.225 --> 29:40.606
- Wow.
- Yeah.

29:40.640 --> 29:42.049
That's why you got to have
a lot of horsepower.

29:42.056 --> 29:43.367
But too much power can get you

29:43.402 --> 29:44.810
in a lot of trouble also.
Oh, really?

29:44.817 --> 29:46.198
- Oh, yeah.
- Exactly right.

29:46.232 --> 29:48.372
Horsepower's not always
the key to success,

29:48.407 --> 29:50.650
but it's always a lot of fun.

29:50.685 --> 29:53.032
Hopefully, you can come back
and try the Barbie Jeep thing.

29:58.900 --> 29:59.400
♪

30:10.878 --> 30:13.363
Guns are a fact
of life around here.

30:13.397 --> 30:16.366
Whether as a means
to defend your isolated home,

30:16.400 --> 30:17.746
get yourself dinner when

30:17.781 --> 30:19.472
there's no place else to get it,

30:19.507 --> 30:21.750
or just for the fun
of shooting stuff,

30:21.785 --> 30:24.581
the feeling that gun ownership
is an absolute right,

30:24.615 --> 30:28.688
immutable and non-negotiable,
runs deep here.

30:28.723 --> 30:30.898
Everybody's backyard
look like this?

30:30.932 --> 30:32.969
- Uh...
- Ours does.

30:33.003 --> 30:34.763
Justin and Ashley McMillion

30:34.798 --> 30:36.248
are the nice couple next door...

30:37.939 --> 30:40.079
If unusually heavily armed.

30:40.114 --> 30:42.047
Yeah!

30:42.081 --> 30:43.980
Our muzzle brakes
are the only kind

30:44.014 --> 30:45.326
that actually reduce recoil,

30:45.360 --> 30:47.259
muzzle rise, and flash.

30:47.293 --> 30:50.503
They own JMac Customs,
a home business that designs

30:50.538 --> 30:52.781
and builds custom
weapons and parts.

30:52.816 --> 30:54.922
So this keeps you on target
and makes sure

30:54.956 --> 30:56.364
that you're safe
while you're shooting.

30:56.371 --> 30:57.579
You put the mag in.

30:57.614 --> 30:58.891
- Safety off.
- Safety off.

30:58.926 --> 31:01.549
You got it.
All right.

31:01.583 --> 31:04.586
Three, two, one.

31:06.726 --> 31:08.349
Now, to be clear,

31:08.383 --> 31:10.420
these are fully automatic
firearms.

31:10.454 --> 31:13.181
They cannot be purchased
legally by individuals

31:13.216 --> 31:15.114
anywhere,

31:15.149 --> 31:16.736
but as they're in the business,

31:16.771 --> 31:18.462
these guys could apply
for special,

31:18.497 --> 31:20.292
highly vetted ATF licenses

31:20.326 --> 31:23.019
for purposes of product
development and testing.

31:23.053 --> 31:25.297
That was just really...
That was a lot of fun.

31:25.331 --> 31:27.368
I'm a child.
What can I say?

31:27.402 --> 31:30.302
Who wants to blow up pumpkins?

31:33.339 --> 31:35.928
Just mixed up
a binary explosive.

31:35.963 --> 31:39.069
♪

31:39.104 --> 31:40.484
Some are small,
and some are big.

31:40.519 --> 31:42.072
You only know
when you shoot it, so.

31:42.107 --> 31:44.972
Ooh, a surprise!
I love surprises.

31:45.006 --> 31:48.423
Three, two, one.

31:51.185 --> 31:55.154
Whatever you feel about gun
rights or access to weapons,

31:55.189 --> 31:57.156
there is an undeniable,

31:57.191 --> 31:59.745
visceral thrill
to blowing shit up.

31:59.779 --> 32:03.576
People who like guns
like them for a reason.

32:03.611 --> 32:05.958
That's a whole lot of America
right there.

32:05.993 --> 32:06.959
Yeah, not mine.

32:08.857 --> 32:12.482
♪

32:12.516 --> 32:16.279
Venison or beef,
with or without cheese.

32:16.313 --> 32:18.281
- Venison and cheese.
- Yeah.

32:18.315 --> 32:20.110
- Wow, a nice selection.
- The only way to go.

32:20.145 --> 32:21.629
That's what I'll have.

32:21.663 --> 32:23.458
Heavenly Father,
we bow in your presence.

32:23.493 --> 32:24.977
We just thank you for this day,

32:25.012 --> 32:26.213
and most of all,
we just thank you

32:26.220 --> 32:27.462
for the liberties and freedoms

32:27.497 --> 32:29.361
that our country provides

32:29.395 --> 32:30.362
and you have provided.

32:30.396 --> 32:32.364
- Amen.
- Amen.

32:32.398 --> 32:34.366
So everybody born
and bred here, or...

32:34.400 --> 32:36.782
- Lisa's from California.
