32:36.816 --> 32:38.501
So when you came here,
that was the first time

32:38.508 --> 32:39.743
you shot a gun, wasn't it?
Yeah.

32:39.750 --> 32:41.994
Show him your arm.

32:42.029 --> 32:44.479
Yeah, show him your tat.
She got an AK tat.

32:44.514 --> 32:46.481
AK tattooed on her arm.

32:46.516 --> 32:48.345
I lived in Canada
for a long time.

32:48.380 --> 32:50.037
Stayed in England
for quite a while.

32:50.071 --> 32:51.624
Sweden for quite a while.

32:51.659 --> 32:53.695
No matter how long I'm gone,
I always come back.

32:53.730 --> 32:55.904
You can't just load the Jeep up
with a bunch of guns

32:55.939 --> 32:58.631
and stay out there
for seven days and, you know...

32:58.666 --> 33:00.668
You can't really do
that anywhere else.

33:00.702 --> 33:02.007
That's probably one of
the greatest things

33:02.014 --> 33:03.498
about West Virginia.

33:03.533 --> 33:06.743
You know, we can enjoy
whatever we want to enjoy.

33:06.777 --> 33:10.126
I'm not trying to force
my opinions on anybody else.

33:10.160 --> 33:12.059
That being said,
we will defend ours.

33:12.093 --> 33:14.647
- Yeah.
- I was guessing.

33:14.682 --> 33:16.235
Yeah.

33:16.270 --> 33:17.926
Look, I grew up
in an environment,

33:17.961 --> 33:21.240
you see somebody at the
supermarket carrying a handgun,

33:21.275 --> 33:24.726
that would be cause
for red alert.

33:24.761 --> 33:27.833
Do you think there can be
common ground between somebody

33:27.867 --> 33:30.939
who grew up absolutely
thinking guns are a bad thing?

33:30.974 --> 33:32.527
I say no.

33:32.562 --> 33:34.177
Okay, you're an honest man,
and I appreciate it.

33:34.184 --> 33:35.254
Why do you...

33:35.289 --> 33:37.360
I'm a responsible gun owner.

33:37.394 --> 33:40.673
Why should I be crippled
in what I'm able to do

33:40.708 --> 33:42.537
as far as protecting my family?

33:42.572 --> 33:45.264
Look, I hear you, but there's
a fair number of people

33:45.299 --> 33:47.611
in this world who are just,
you know,

33:47.646 --> 33:49.786
too dumb to pour piss
out of a boot.

33:49.820 --> 33:52.754
You know, 90-year-old
drivers in Florida,

33:52.789 --> 33:55.343
they still got their license,
but should they be driving?

33:55.378 --> 33:57.276
- Right.
- A few years ago,

33:57.311 --> 33:58.795
my father was involved
in a shooting

33:58.829 --> 34:00.969
at his pharmacy
that he works at.

34:01.004 --> 34:02.454
A man came in.
He had a weapon.

34:02.488 --> 34:03.696
My dad conceal carries.

34:03.731 --> 34:05.077
He has a license
to conceal carry.

34:05.112 --> 34:06.596
He drew his weapon and fired.

34:06.630 --> 34:08.804
If they take guns away
from law-abiding citizens,

34:08.839 --> 34:11.187
then it's just gonna be
the criminals that have it.

34:13.637 --> 34:15.087
It should be pointed out...

34:15.121 --> 34:18.297
It has to be pointed out,
faced head-on...

34:18.331 --> 34:20.299
That shortly after
we filmed here,

34:20.333 --> 34:23.784
a gunman in Las Vegas,
with a perfectly legal weapon,

34:23.820 --> 34:27.547
fired off 1,100 rounds
in ten minutes,

34:27.581 --> 34:32.967
wounding 422 people
and killing 58.

34:33.001 --> 34:35.418
Shortly after that, 17 students

34:35.452 --> 34:37.420
were murdered
in Parkland, Florida,

34:37.454 --> 34:41.009
with a legally purchased
semi-automatic rifle,

34:41.043 --> 34:43.804
and the list goes on,
with victims of mass shootings

34:43.840 --> 34:46.152
that have happened
since this conversation

34:46.187 --> 34:47.637
measured in the hundreds,

34:47.670 --> 34:49.949
so there is that
to think about too.

34:49.984 --> 34:51.848
I don't know whether
the founding fathers

34:51.882 --> 34:54.092
anticipated
the kind of firepower

34:54.126 --> 34:55.402
that we played with today.

34:55.438 --> 34:58.096
We live in a different world.

34:58.130 --> 35:01.168
There are the nice people who
live next door who like guns,

35:01.202 --> 35:04.343
and, unfortunately, there seem
to be a whole lot of people

35:04.378 --> 35:07.760
who aren't nice at all.

35:09.452 --> 35:12.006
Get behind cover!

35:12.040 --> 35:15.941
- Oh, my God, oh, my God!
- Go back, go back!

35:17.805 --> 35:21.188
One would hope there is
at least some middle ground.

35:21.222 --> 35:22.672
Oh, my God.

35:34.062 --> 35:34.562
♪

35:38.860 --> 35:41.173
They call this
Burning Fork Holler.

35:41.208 --> 35:43.037
What is a holler?

35:43.071 --> 35:47.317
I mean, it's spelled "hollow,"
but it's pronounced "holler."

35:47.352 --> 35:53.358
A holler, to me, is where
everybody is united.

35:53.392 --> 35:55.877
Everybody sticks with
one another

35:55.912 --> 35:58.052
and takes up for one another.

35:58.086 --> 35:58.586
♪

36:07.268 --> 36:10.168
Lola Kline is a single
mother of four children,

36:10.202 --> 36:12.929
and, in many ways, emblematic
of both the difficulties

36:12.963 --> 36:16.208
and inherent strengths
of people around here.

36:16.243 --> 36:18.348
Where do you find them?
In the trees or on the ground?

36:18.383 --> 36:20.937
- Trees.
- Mostly up the trees?

36:20.971 --> 36:24.389
Squirrels are more like-
it's a waiting game.

36:24.423 --> 36:28.082
Find us a place to sit
and watch for movement.

36:29.152 --> 36:31.430
She and her best friend,
LaShawna Huff,

36:31.465 --> 36:33.674
hunt together,
raise kids together,

36:33.708 --> 36:36.090
and do their best to get by
in a changing world

36:36.124 --> 36:38.679
that can get very hard.

36:38.713 --> 36:42.407
We got to keep our eye out,
too, timber rattlers.

36:42.441 --> 36:44.443
They good eating, rattlesnake?

36:44.478 --> 36:45.962
I've never ate one.

36:45.996 --> 36:48.102
I seen a rattlesnake
coming this way,

36:48.136 --> 36:49.966
and I go that way.

36:51.485 --> 36:53.452
When you'd first go hunting,
how old were you?

36:53.487 --> 36:56.214
My grandpa took me
when I was about six.

36:56.248 --> 36:58.802
I just love this place.

36:58.837 --> 37:01.391
Having a bad day, you can
always go up in the mountains.

37:01.426 --> 37:03.635
All that changes.

37:08.018 --> 37:08.518
♪

37:32.871 --> 37:33.371
♪

37:42.052 --> 37:45.918
My mom, she used to cook it
and fix squirrel gravy.

37:45.953 --> 37:48.438
Lola's neighbor's name
may be Drana Lester,

37:48.473 --> 37:50.958
but everybody here
calls her Mom.

37:50.992 --> 37:53.823
58 years.
I was born and raised here.

37:53.857 --> 37:56.204
Do you ever think about leaving?

37:56.239 --> 37:58.172
No.

37:58.206 --> 38:01.209
She often cooks and helps
look after the kids.

38:01.244 --> 38:02.832
Biscuit?
Homemade biscuits.

38:02.866 --> 38:04.489
Homemade gravy.
Fried taters.

38:04.523 --> 38:06.042
Fried potatoes, excellent.

38:06.076 --> 38:08.976
And Lola does her best
to look after her.

38:09.010 --> 38:11.530
That's what people do
in the hollers.

38:11.565 --> 38:13.049
Dear Lord, we come
to you this day.

38:13.083 --> 38:15.293
Thank you for this food
and bless the hands

38:15.327 --> 38:16.846
that fixed this food.

38:16.880 --> 38:19.297
Thank you for each
and every living day. Amen.

38:19.331 --> 38:23.715
Amen, and thank you for
letting us make more friends.

38:23.749 --> 38:25.544
Thank you for having me.

38:25.579 --> 38:28.720
Mmm-mmm. I've been waiting
all day for this.

38:28.754 --> 38:30.404
Are you working on a farm
nearby, is that right?

38:30.411 --> 38:31.654
Yes.

38:31.688 --> 38:33.380
After strip mines are done here,

38:33.414 --> 38:34.691
the land's usually-

38:34.726 --> 38:36.624
I mean, it's just useless.

38:36.659 --> 38:38.661
So we're trying
to make a purpose.

38:38.695 --> 38:40.318
Pumpkins, watermelon.

38:40.352 --> 38:42.906
We're just trying to figure out
what will grow on it.

38:42.941 --> 38:46.254
- So there's life after coal?
- There's life after coal.

38:46.289 --> 38:48.395
For about eight years,
I worked on strip mines.

38:48.429 --> 38:50.466
I could probably get a job now,

38:50.500 --> 38:52.039
but I don't want
to mess up a good thing.

38:52.053 --> 38:53.848
So what do you think
about that squirrel?

38:53.883 --> 38:55.505
- Oh, man, it's good.
- Good, ain't it?

38:55.540 --> 38:57.093
Thank you.

38:57.127 --> 38:59.578
They call it wild
and wonderful West Virginia.

38:59.613 --> 39:02.685
It is.
And your girls are how old?

39:02.719 --> 39:06.551
My girls are nine, eight,
six, and three.

39:06.585 --> 39:08.035
You taught any of them
to shoot yet?

39:08.069 --> 39:09.719
- Yeah, all of them can shoot.
- All of them?

39:09.726 --> 39:11.176
All of them.

39:11.210 --> 39:12.867
They think their mommy's
a big hero too

39:12.902 --> 39:14.766
because she killed that
big buck last year.

39:14.800 --> 39:16.595
Yeah, how big was this thing?

39:16.630 --> 39:18.597
- 250. Weighed 250 pounds.
- Yeah.

39:18.632 --> 39:20.703
You drag that thing out
of the woods yourself?

39:20.737 --> 39:22.290
- Mm-hmm.
- Dress it?

39:22.325 --> 39:23.602
- Yes.
- Cook it?

39:23.637 --> 39:25.604
- Yep.
- We don't rely on nobody.

39:25.639 --> 39:27.081
Yeah, there ain't nothing
I can't do,

39:27.088 --> 39:28.635
and if I don't know
how to do it, I'll learn.

39:28.642 --> 39:30.747
We're not a bunch
of pregnant women,

39:30.782 --> 39:32.784
barefooted with no teeth.

39:32.818 --> 39:34.613
I got all of mine, you see?

39:36.339 --> 39:38.893
What's the best thing about
living in this area,

39:38.928 --> 39:40.964
and what's the...
What's the worst thing?

39:40.999 --> 39:44.312
The best thing
is the people here.

39:44.347 --> 39:46.798
You always got somebody that
has your back, no matter what.

39:46.832 --> 39:48.903
Like, I couldn't
move away from here.

39:48.938 --> 39:51.630
I'd be so sick.
Homesick.

39:51.665 --> 39:52.969
There's probably nobody
in these hollers

39:52.976 --> 39:54.875
that I couldn't go say,

39:54.909 --> 39:57.774
"Hey, I need... I'm hungry.
Would you fix me a sandwich?"

39:57.809 --> 40:00.639
And the worst thing?

40:00.674 --> 40:04.919
See somebody that's on pills,

40:04.954 --> 40:08.647
or drunk,
or out here just fighting.

40:13.825 --> 40:17.173
- What can you do?
- Pray for them.

40:17.207 --> 40:20.452
That's all we can do.

