Lost Creek Farm is their place.

45:19.475 --> 45:22.236
♪

45:22.271 --> 45:25.067
A working farm
they're rebuilding by hand.

45:25.101 --> 45:27.483
♪

45:27.517 --> 45:30.658
And the nucleus
of that effort is the garden.

45:30.693 --> 45:33.040
♪

45:36.078 --> 45:39.495
♪

45:39.529 --> 45:41.635
We have two different varieties

45:41.669 --> 45:43.154
that we're picking today.

45:43.188 --> 45:44.638
The one are the Logan Giants.

45:44.672 --> 45:46.985
This seed is Logan Giant seed,

45:47.020 --> 45:50.057
and they're an heirloom
strain of bean,

45:50.092 --> 45:51.990
and I've had these
seeds for 40 years.

45:52.025 --> 45:54.096
I saved these for 40 years.

45:54.130 --> 45:55.925
This guy down at the end
of the table,

45:55.960 --> 45:57.824
Lou, is in his 90s.

45:57.858 --> 45:59.163
He said it's important
for somebody

45:59.170 --> 46:00.792
to carry on these traditions

46:00.827 --> 46:03.519
and gave me his stock
of heirloom beans this year.

46:03.553 --> 46:08.110
This is what heirloom looks
like outside of Holy Foods.

46:08.144 --> 46:10.906
Bloody Butcher corn,

46:10.940 --> 46:12.839
Fat Horse beans,

46:12.873 --> 46:14.495
Candy Roaster squash,

46:14.530 --> 46:17.291
and Homer Fike's
Yellow Ox Heart tomatoes.

46:17.326 --> 46:19.984
Nice and soft, and it's like
a really sweet green tomato.

46:20.018 --> 46:23.608
These ingredients define
a near-lost time and flavor.

46:23.642 --> 46:25.472
This is an Italian
heirloom beet that

46:25.506 --> 46:27.501
was brought to West Virginia
by an Italian immigrant,

46:27.508 --> 46:29.372
so it's, like,
it's called a Chioggia.

46:29.407 --> 46:32.617
The story of hardship
and resourcefulness.

46:32.651 --> 46:35.723
We've got some sweet corn
chowder.

46:35.758 --> 46:38.726
We're gonna just, like, drizzle
a little bit of this

46:38.761 --> 46:40.487
nettles and wild apples.

46:40.521 --> 46:42.938
Next, we've got these crackers.

46:42.972 --> 46:44.802
They're broken communion wafers.

46:44.836 --> 46:46.734
You know, the way
that Appalachian food

46:46.769 --> 46:47.943
has always worked

46:47.977 --> 46:49.289
is you work with
within your means,

46:49.323 --> 46:51.049
and you create something
pretty special

46:51.084 --> 46:52.844
out of what you have
at your disposal,

46:52.879 --> 46:55.467
and we've kind of suffered
from this in a way.

46:55.502 --> 46:58.229
It created this sort of rush
towards the middle class

46:58.263 --> 46:59.817
and a rush towards
the perception

46:59.851 --> 47:01.232
that we're better than the foods

47:01.266 --> 47:02.647
that we used to have to eat.

47:02.681 --> 47:04.021
- Mm-hmm.
- Yeah, I think we were taught

47:04.028 --> 47:05.546
a lot to be embarrassed

47:05.581 --> 47:07.341
of our, you know,
hillbilly past, you know?

47:07.376 --> 47:08.756
- Oh, absolutely.
- Right.

47:08.791 --> 47:10.268
I remember coming home
from school and my dad

47:10.275 --> 47:11.545
having hog's head
on the kitchen table

47:11.552 --> 47:13.347
making head cheese
and sauce, like,

47:13.382 --> 47:15.556
I'd been mortified if somebody
came over and saw that.

47:15.591 --> 47:17.765
Yeah, a friend of mine's
grandmother once told me,

47:17.800 --> 47:19.795
"You know, we used to make this
because we were poor.

47:19.802 --> 47:22.736
Now we make it
because it's effing good."

47:25.532 --> 47:27.775
- Ooh, what's that?
- This is some

47:27.810 --> 47:29.363
buttermilk fried rabbit,

47:29.398 --> 47:30.599
rabbit that we raise here
on the farm.

47:30.606 --> 47:31.918
Oh, yes.

47:31.952 --> 47:35.783
A little bit of chowchow,
some fresh maple syrup.

47:38.821 --> 47:41.272
♪

47:41.306 --> 47:43.688
Is it gross that we slaughter
rabbits right behind us?

47:43.722 --> 47:44.792
Yeah.

47:47.485 --> 47:50.522
This is some venison
harvested from the woods here.

47:50.557 --> 47:53.560
It's got a wild chicory
root rub to it.

47:53.594 --> 47:55.769
♪

47:55.803 --> 47:58.806
Some chanterelles and sorghum
syrup and some wild pears.

47:58.841 --> 48:00.567
Wow.

48:00.601 --> 48:02.569
Mike and Amy's friends
are a cross section of people

48:02.603 --> 48:05.192
invested in
West Virginia's potential.

48:05.227 --> 48:06.573
Which we've been drinking here,

48:06.607 --> 48:08.299
the young or
the old school cider?

48:08.333 --> 48:11.958
We actually came across
a recipe from 1822

48:11.992 --> 48:13.891
with elderberry and cider,

48:13.925 --> 48:15.547
and it's a native plant here,

48:15.582 --> 48:18.757
so we put a little bit in there
to see what it would do,

48:18.792 --> 48:20.242
and it came out wonderful.

48:20.276 --> 48:22.485
You're using only
West Virginia apples?

48:22.520 --> 48:24.453
I am only using
West Virginia apples.

48:24.487 --> 48:28.836
- That can't be cost effective.
- It can and can't be.

48:28.871 --> 48:31.667
Nobody's talking about money
at this table though.

48:32.875 --> 48:34.981
This is another thing for me.

48:35.015 --> 48:37.010
We're often talked about as
being this impoverished state.

48:37.017 --> 48:40.918
We are rich, I mean, as can be,
in food and the things

48:40.952 --> 48:44.335
that we make as a culture
and as a community.

48:44.369 --> 48:45.992
When you're living on the land

48:46.026 --> 48:47.786
and doing what
your ancestors did,

48:47.821 --> 48:51.169
you feel a connection that
you can't get anywhere else.

48:51.204 --> 48:53.068
You know, you look at something

48:53.102 --> 48:55.415
as simple as these pole beans.

48:55.449 --> 48:57.486
It took our community
to save that seed,

48:57.520 --> 48:59.833
and every time we put
food on the plate,

48:59.867 --> 49:01.524
there's a story about the way

49:01.559 --> 49:05.252
that people have always kind of
bound together to survive.

49:08.807 --> 49:09.307
♪

